5.0 out of 5 starsI love this new music by Norah Jones.
By Robert G Yokoyama VINE VOICE on October 7, 2016
Format: MP3 Music
I love this new album from Norah Jones. My favorite song is "Flipside". I love the upbeat groovy piano playing talent that Norah shows here. I love the song "Once I Had A Laugh". The trumpet playing by Dave Guy is really soothing here. This song relaxes me. There is another song entitled "Don't Be Denied". This song is about a young singer following their dream. This song makes me feel empowered to pursue my dream to become an actor. Norah did not write this. The great Neil Young wrote this song, but the lyrics still resonates with me. I love the smooth saxophone playing on the song "Burn".This is not a love song, but the instrumental arrangements make this a perfect song to listen to with a special woman. I love the song entitled "Peace". This song motivates me to find inner peace every day. The saxophone playing by Wayne Shorter is superb throughout this album. I am always searching for a source of hope that I will find a soul mate soon. "It's A Wonderful Time for Love" is the perfect inspiration for me. This song reminds me to stay open minded to the possibility of finding love. I love the bass playing on this song very much. I love the instrumental track entitled "Sleeping Wild". Even though this song does not have words, the music touches me. I think this song reaffirms my belief that I should approach life with a sense of wonder. This tune makes me feel that I still have so much to learn in life. I really enjoy listening to this new album by Norah Jones. Her vocals are strong, and the songs are musically arranged beautifully.

5.0 out of 5 starsThe Jazz Album I've Long Wanted Norah Jones to Record
By Tom Croft on October 7, 2016
Format: MP3 Music Verified Purchase
Day Breaks is the kind of album I've been wishing Norah Jones would record for a long time (I'm also a big fan of the album New York City by the Peter Malick group, on which Norah appeared as the featured vocalist). Hearing her record some genuine jazz tunes (some of them originals, even!) with great instrumentalists like Wayne Shorter, John Patitucci, and Brian Blade makes for some very enjoyable listening. Duke Ellington's haunting "Fleurette Africaine" makes a great closing track for this excellent album. Highly recommended.

5.0 out of 5 starsSimply amazing
By Obi Wan TOP 100 REVIEWER on October 7, 2016
Format: MP3 Music
Remember that really bad album Norah Jones did? Yeah me neither...because she's AMAZING!!!!!

10 seconds into this album's open track and I felt like I was fully immersed in a smoke filled 1940's late night jazz club. And it was awesome! I gave this a 5 star review, but I feel that the 5 star system is limiting here. This is a SIX star album that is a cut above the rest.

- Burn. Soft smooth jazz. It's got a slow but steady beat with Jones' signature slightly raspy vocals that sound like the heavens are filling the world with song. The lyrics that superficially deal with burning (but have deeper meaning) fit perfectly with that image she creates in your mind of a smoke fill jazz club.

- Tragedy. The tone gets a little more upbeat here. But it's still that 40's jazz sound with the bass in the background. The theme of the song isn't as upbeat as the music. It's The first 50 seconds are Jones literally just repeating the phrase "It's a Tragedy" which you'd think wouldn't be cool...but she makes it awesome. With her voice she could sign the tax code and I'd feel mellow and relaxed by it.

- Flipside. You know what's cool about jazz piano? Everything. This one is much faster than you're used to with Jones for the most part. It's got great lyrics and a steady beat that keeps you pumped up despite it's relatively calm vocals. It's the background music that gives this on energy. Jones' voice just makes it awesome awesome. In fact I'm going to get tired of typing about how great her voice is. So let's just stipulate from here on out that she sounds like a choir of angels from here on out...

- It's a Wonderful Time For Love. Starts off with that slow bass / piano combo. So you're forced to start dancing even if you're sitting down.Read more ›

5.0 out of 5 starsAs Cool As It Gets
By Jetset on October 7, 2016
Format: Audio CD Verified Purchase
What an amazing record! "Day Breaks" is Norah's best album yet. There's something really cool running through this CD, from the first song to the last, and the music makes you feel like you just walked into a jazz bar somewhere in New York City. And as you enter the place, you can hear the sound of a tight band of musicians on stage led by a sweet-looking piano player with a magical voice.

So, from the first notes of "Burn" through "Tragedy" & "Flipside" and into "It's a Wonderful Time for Love" to "And Then There Was You' - you realize wow this is great stuff. And so you keep listening and taking it all in - then the title cut & "Sleeping Wild" & "Carry On" come on & "Fleurette Africaine" (where Norah beautifully duels with jazz legend Wayne Shorter). All of these amazing tunes only draw you deeper into the dream and before you know it, sometime later - it's the bartender who wakes you up to tell you: "Hey buddy, that's it for tonight - come back tomorrow night - she'll be here again!"

That's what it felt like - so I gotta hand it to Norah - she really delivered this time!
